		<item>
			<title>Does this game capture the spirit of Conan?</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?t=58433&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Mon, 02 Jun 2008 17:23:06 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[I'm just interested in what other Conaniphiles think about how well they captured the essence of the Hyborian setting.

Personally I think they did a great job on the "mature content" angle. I think the game has just the right amount of language, nudity, blood, etc... to make it feel like a...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>I'm just interested in what other Conaniphiles think about how well they captured the essence of the Hyborian setting.<br />
<br />
Personally I think they did a great job on the &quot;mature content&quot; angle. I think the game has just the right amount of language, nudity, blood, etc... to make it feel like a &quot;mature&quot; game without going overboard.<br />
<br />
I think the quests are also pretty good, although they're often too close to standard goody-goody fantasy quests for my taste (especially in Aquilonia, the less Mitra in the game the better I think).<br />
<br />
The world itself is also well done, but I think here they might have mis-stepped a bit. If you read the Howard Conan stories, almost all of them feature Conan in very exotic locales. That's kind of the whole point of them. He's almost always in fantasy analogues of Africa, middle-eastern nations, India and so on. In the game, however, two thirds of the content is in Cimmeria and Aquilonia, places are much more recognizably &quot;european&quot;.<br />
<br />
I think it's no accident that my two favority zones so far have been Tortage and Kopshef province, both of which I think are much more appropriate Conan settings. Hopefully they'll flesh out the rest of world and we'll be able to go to places like Hyrkania, Vendhya, or Zamora, all of which actually featured much more in the stories than Cimmeria.<br />
<br />
Anyone else have thoughts on this?</div>

]]></content:encoded>
